A common FSM style uses one block for state registers and one block for next-state/output logic.

```systemverilog
typedef enum logic [2:0] {
  IDLE = 3'b001,
  RUN  = 3'b010,
  DONE = 3'b100
} state_t;

state_t state_q, state_d;

always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n) begin
  if (!rst_n) state_q <= IDLE;
  else        state_q <= state_d;
end

always_comb begin
  state_d = state_q;
  done    = 1'b0;
  unique case (state_q)
    IDLE: if (start) state_d = RUN;
    RUN:  if (last)  state_d = DONE;
    DONE: begin done = 1'b1; state_d = IDLE; end
    default: state_d = IDLE;
  endcase
end
```

The important part is that control and data move through the pipeline together.

```systemverilog
always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n) begin
  if (!rst_n) begin
    valid_q <= 1'b0;
    data_q  <= '0;
  end else if (ready_to_load) begin
    valid_q <= in_valid;
    data_q  <= in_data;
  end
end
```

This pattern lets reset assert immediately, then deassert through flops in the destination clock domain.

```systemverilog
